entry.title: [//gpu] Change how ProduceSkia() chooses Ganesh vs. Graphite
entry.content:
SharedImageBacking::ProduceSkia() currently assumes that if the

GrContext is not present, then we are using Graphite and hence

graphite_context() should be present. However, this is not universally

true (see [1]). This CL changes this function to go to Ganesh or

Graphite based on the GrContextType.



Note: Before Graphite was introduced into this function, there was

nothing checking that the GrContext was non-null [1]. Hence, this CL

also does not introduce any such check. Any issues that come up in

individual backings will now be properly surfaced as crashes at the

level of those individual backings. This CL *does* add a CHECK that

the GrContextType on a call to ProduceSkia() is not `kNone`. When the

GrContextType is `kNone` Skia initialization is skipped, meaning that

both gr_context() and graphite_context() will be null. Hence, we would

already be hitting the current CHECK(graphite_context()) in this case.



[1] https://issues.chromium.org/u/1/issues/41495250#comment5

[2] https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4480449



Bug: 41495250

entry.title: Fix dangling pointer issues in system_signals_service unittests.
entry.content:
The constructors for these unittests create a MockFileSystemService

sub-object owned by a unique_ptr and moves them to

`${platform_}system_signals_service_`. The test holds on to the

sub-objects via raw_ptr.



This causes dangling pointer detection to fire during test destruction

as the ordering of the member variable (in the unittest) causes the

owning object to be destroyed first (thus making the sub-object

dangling -- for an instant).



Re-ordering the raw_ptr sub-object such that it is destroyed first

avoids this problem.

entry.title: webui: add a preload manager for top chrome WebUIs
entry.content:
Add WebUIContentsPreloadManager that can preload a WebContents with

top chrome WebUI resources, such that

* it maintains at most one WebContents instance at anytime.

* it creates a new WebContents when the preloaded one is taken.

* it redirects the preloaded contents to the requested WebUI if needed.

* it swaps the WebContents if requested under a different Profile.

* it stops preloading new WebContents if under heavy memory pressure.

* it shows the preloaded renderer as "Tool: Preloaded Renderer for UI"

in the task manager.



This patch is gated by a new feature PreloadTopChromeWebUI. Actual

support for preloading will be in following patches that integrate the

manager with BrowserView and WebUIContentsWrapper.



This patch has no behavior changes.

entry.title: saved_desks: Fix missing incognito icon
entry.content:
This icon is supposed to show in the dialog that warns a user that the

desk they are trying to save contains unsupported windows. The code is

using ui::ThemedVectorIcon to create an ImageSkia, which is then passed

to apps::CreateStandardIconImage.



The issue is that the image we get from ThemedVectorIcon has no "reps",

and CreateStandardIconImage does all of its work by looping over the

reps in the source image. This ultimately means that it produces a

completely empty image.



Fixed by calling EnsureRepsForSupportedScales.

entry.title: Use EGL_ANGLE_global_fence_sync
entry.content:
Chrome has an implicit assumption that due to context virtualization,

signaling a fence in one context results in synchronization with _all_

contexts that have previously made submissions.



This is not per EGL spec, and does not work with ANGLE's Vulkan backend

(which is optimized for multi-threaded applications). However, ANGLE's

Vulkan backend provides this functionality through the

EGL_ANGLE_global_fence_sync extension. This change makes sure Chrome

prefers use of EGL sync objects provided by that extension such that the

above assumption is satisfied.



Bug: b/318721705

entry.title: [views_ax] Introduce ViewAccessibility setters for PosInSet and SetSize
entry.content:
This CL introduces



* ViewAccessibility::SetPosInSet

* ViewAccessibility::SetSetSize

* ViewAccessibility::ClearPosInSet

* ViewAccessibility::ClearSetSize



We'll replace the callers of OverridePosInSet and ClearPosInSetOverride in the

next CL, and remove those overrides quickly after.



Previously, OverridePosInSet and ClearPosInSetOverride took care of not only the PosInSet attribute, but also the SetSize. There could

be valid cases where the set size changes but the PosInSet doesn't,

so we prefer to split those setters into atomic setters. It will also

make it easier to add automatic event generation per attribute if

needed.



This results in the same behavior, and eventually we will remove the

override functions.
